`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`
- The `useState`/`useEffect` split is the key architectural insight: React state controls *which* GLB is mounted (declarative), while anime.js drives *when* the swap happens (imperative). These two concerns must stay in separate layers — trying to merge them causes React/animation lifecycle conflicts.
- The new `ToolGLBModel` instance starts already at `-lowerY` when it mounts because `swapAnimRef.current.y` is still at its nadir from the DOWN tween. The UP tween is already running by then. No "start from zero" reset is needed.
- `buildSwapDown/UpParams` returning plain `{ targets, y, duration, easing, complete }` objects (not anime.js types) is the same "testable seam" pattern used throughout this codebase (`resolveGLBPath`, `computeSwayOffset`, etc.) — pure functions that can be unit tested without any runtime context.
